  "prompt": "What function do we use in Java in place of cin>> in C++?",
  "response": "In Java, the equivalent function for reading user input from the console, similar to `cin >>` in C++, is achieved using the `Scanner` class. Here is an example of how to use the `Scanner` class to read different types of input:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n\n        // Reading a string\n        System.out.print(\"Enter a string: \");\n        String inputString = scanner.nextLine();\n        System.out.println(\"You entered: \" + inputString);\n\n        // Reading an integer\n        System.out.print(\"Enter an integer: \");\n        int inputInt = scanner.nextInt();\n        System.out.println(\"You entered: \" + inputInt);\n\n        // Reading a double\n        System.out.print(\"Enter a double: \");\n        double inputDouble = scanner.nextDouble();\n        System.out.println(\"You entered: \" + inputDouble);\n\n        // If you want to read another type after nextInt or nextDouble, it's good practice to consume the remaining newline\n        scanner.nextLine(); \n\n        // Reading another string after consuming newline\n        System.out.print(\"Enter another string: \");\n        String anotherString = scanner.nextLine();\n        System.out.println(\"You entered: \" + anotherString);\n\n        scanner.close();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe `Scanner` class provides several methods for reading different types of input:\n- `nextLine()` for reading a line of text,\n- `nextInt()` for reading an integer,\n- `nextDouble()` for reading a double,\n- And other methods like `nextFloat()`, `nextBoolean()`, etc.\n\nBe sure to close the `Scanner` object once you have finished using it to avoid resource leaks, which is done using `scanner.close()`.",
